<section xml:id="sec-algebra-of-ideals">
	<title>Algebra of ideals</title>
	<definition xml:id="ideal-generated-by-subset">
		<title>(Ideal generated by a subset)</title>
		<statement>
			Let <m>R</m> be a ring and <m>S</m> be a subset of <m>R</m>. The <term>left ideal generated by <m>S</m></term> (resp., <term>right ideal generated by <m>S</m></term>, <term>ideal generated by <m>S</m></term>) is denoted by <m>(S)</m> and it is defined as follows.
			<md><mrow>\text{Left ideal generated by }S:\quad\amp (S)=\left\{\sum_{i=1}^n x_is_i:x_i\in R, s_i\in S\text{ and }n\in\N\right\};</mrow><mrow>\text{Right ideal generated by }S:\quad\amp (S)=\left\{\sum_{i=1}^n s_iy_i:y_i\in R, s_i\in S\text{ and }n\in\N\right\};</mrow><mrow>\text{Ideal generated by }S:\quad\amp (S)=\left\{\sum_{i=1}^n x_is_iy_i:x_i,y_i\in R, s_i\in S\text{ and }n\in\N\right\}.</mrow></md>
		</statement>
	</definition>

<lemma xml:id="algebra-of-ideals">
	<statement>
		Let <m>\mathfrak{a}</m> and <m>\mathfrak{b}</m> be left ideals (resp., right ideals, two-sided ideals) in a ring <m>R</m>. Then following are left ideals (resp., right ideals, two-sided ideals):
		<ol>
			<li><title>[Smallest left ideal containing both <m>\mfa</m> and <m>\mfb</m>]</title><m>\mathfrak{a}+\mathfrak{b}=\{a+b:a\in\mathfrak{a}\text{ and }b\in\mathfrak{b}\}</m>. More generally if <m>\mfa_i</m> are left ideals of <m>R</m> then 
			<me>\sum\mfa_i=\left\{\sum_ix_i:x_i\in\mfa_i\text{ and all but finitely many}\quad x_i=0\right\}.</me>
			</li>
			<li><title>[Smallest left ideal contained in both <m>\mfa</m> and <m>\mfb</m>]</title><m>\mfa\cap\mfb</m></li>
			<li><title>[Left ideal generated by <m>ab</m>]</title><m>\mfa\mfb=\left(\{ab:a\in\mfa,b\in\mfb\}\right)</m></li>
			<li><title>[Powers of a left ideal]</title><m>\mfa^n=(\{a^n:a\in\mfa\text{ and }a^n=\underbrace{a\cdot a\cdots a}_{n\text{-times}}\})</m> when <m>n\gt 0</m> and we assume <m>\mfa^0=(1)=R</m>.</li>
			<li>If <m>\mfa,\mfb</m> and <m>\mathfrak{c}</m> are ideals (i.e., two-sided ideals) in <m>R</m> then we have following identities.
			<md><mrow>\mfa(\mfb+\mfc)\amp=\mfa\mfb+\mfa\mfc</mrow><mrow>(\mfa+\mfb)\mfc\amp=\mfa\mfc+\mfb\mfc</mrow><mrow>\text{If}\;\mfb\subseteq\mfa\;\text{or}\;\mfc\subseteq\mfa\quad\text{then}\quad\amp\mfa\cap(\mfb+\mfc)=(\mfa\cap\mfb)+(\mfa\cap\mfc)</mrow></md>
		</li>
		</ol>
	</statement>
</lemma>
<proof>
	Left to the reader. We prove more general version of (2) below.
</proof>
<remark>
	<statement>
		In general <m>\mfa\mfb\subsetneq\mfa\cap\mfb\subsetneq\mfa+\mfb</m>.
	</statement>
</remark>
<lemma xml:id="intersection-of-ideals-is-ideal">
		<statement>
			Let <m>I</m> be a nonempty indexing set, and let <m>\mathfrak{a}_i</m> (<m>i\in I</m>) be left ideals (resp., right ideals, two-sided ideals) of a ring <m>R</m>. Then <m>\bigcap_i\mathfrak{a}_i</m> is a left ideal (resp., a right ideal, two-sided ideal) of <m>R</m>.
		</statement>
	</lemma>
	<proof>
		We only show that the intersection of left ideals is a left ideal. Suppose that <m>x,y\in\bigcap_i\mathfrak{a}_i</m>. Then, since each <m>\mathfrak{a}_i</m> is a subgroup, <m>x-y\in\mathfrak{a}_i</m> for each <m>i</m>. Hence <m>\bigcap_i\mathfrak{a}_i</m> is a subgroup. For any <m>r\in R</m> and any <m>x\in\bigcap_i\mathfrak{a}_i</m>, we have <m>rx\in\mathfrak{a}_i</m> because every <m>\mathfrak{a}_i</m> is a left ideal. Thus, <m>rx\in\bigcap_i\mathfrak{a}_i</m> and we get the result.
	</proof>

	<observation>
		<statement>
			In view of <xref ref="intersection-of-ideals-is-ideal"/> a left ideal (resp., right ideal, two-sided ideal) generated by <m>S</m> is the intersection of all left ideals in <m>R</m> containing <m>S</m>, i.e.,
			<me>(S)=\bigcap_{\substack{S\subseteq I\\I\text{ a left ideal}}}I.</me>
		</statement>
	</observation>
</section>